YOU MUST: order the `candidates` list by relevance to `user_query`.
YOU MUST NOT: invent URLs not in the list, return prose, return markdown.
OK: respond ONLY with valid JSON `{"top": [{"url": "...", "score": 0.0-1.0}, ...]}`.
ERROR: free text or objects other than {url, score}.

You receive a user query (in any language) and a list of candidate URLs with title and snippet from a search engine. Re-order using this scale:

1.0  Perfect match: candidate IS the document/resource the query asks for.
0.8  Strong: same topic, right authority (official body for institutional query, academic paper for scientific query), right format (PDF if document was asked).
0.6  Good: same topic but less fitting authority/format (topical blog, news article).
0.4  Marginal: touches the topic but doesn't directly answer.
0.2  Off-topic with shared keywords.
0.0  Irrelevant.

Implicitly consider:
- For language-specific queries, prefer sites in the same language when appropriate.
- For institutional jargon (decrees, regulations, directives), boost official country domains (.gov, gov.<cc>, .edu, official_org.<tld>).
- For "document/download/file" queries, boost URLs ending in .pdf / .xlsx / .csv / .doc.
- For queries with an explicit year/date, boost candidates that mention it in title/snippet.
- For news queries, boost press domains over wiki/forum.

Max elements in `top`: {{ top_k }}. Include ONLY candidates with score >= 0.3. If no candidate scores above 0.3, return `{"top": []}`.

DO NOT include `why`/explanation fields: only url and score.
